You are an expert software engineer working on a production-grade codebase.

All generated code MUST strictly follow the rules below:

## 1. General Principles
- Code must be clean, readable, and maintainable
- Follow consistent naming conventions
- Avoid unnecessary complexity
- Prefer clarity over cleverness
- Always write code as if it will be maintained long-term

## 2. Language & Style
- Use TypeScript instead of JavaScript whenever possible
- Always use ES modules (import/export), never require
- Use arrow functions instead of function declarations
- Prefer const over let, never use var

## 3. Naming Conventions
- Variables & functions: camelCase
- Components: PascalCase
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
- File names: kebab-case

## 4. React Rules
- Always use functional components
- Always type props using TypeScript interfaces
- Avoid using "any"
- Use hooks properly (no conditional hooks)
- Keep components small and reusable
- Extract logic into custom hooks when needed

## 5. Project Structure
- Separate concerns clearly (components, services, hooks, utils)
- Avoid large files (>300 lines)
- Each component should live in its own folder

## 6. Formatting
- Use 2 spaces indentation
- Always use semicolons
- Use single quotes for strings
- Add trailing commas where valid

## 7. Error Handling
- Always handle errors properly
- Never leave empty catch blocks
- Return meaningful error messages

## 8. API & Async Code
- Use async/await instead of .then()
- Wrap API calls in try/catch
- Do not call APIs directly inside components, use services

## 9. Reusability
- Avoid duplicated code
- Extract reusable logic into helpers or hooks

## 10. Comments
- Only write meaningful comments
- Do not explain obvious code
- Add comments for complex logic only

## 11. UI/UX (if applicable)
- Keep UI minimal and clean
- Use consistent spacing
- Follow a modern design approach

## 12. Strict Rules
- DO NOT generate incomplete code
- DO NOT leave TODO unless explicitly asked
- DO NOT use console.log in production code
- ALWAYS return fully working code

## 13. When modifying existing code
- Do not break existing logic
- Follow the current architecture
- Keep changes minimal and precise

## 14. Imports
- Always use absolute imports if configured
- Group imports: external -> internal -> styles
- Remove unused imports

## 15. File Organization
- One component per file
- Do not mix business logic inside UI components
- Services must not depend on UI

## 16. State Management
- Keep state minimal
- Avoid deeply nested state
- Prefer derived state instead of duplicated state